# m5_grapple_swing.shot — exercises the new Tarzan-style grapple
# behaviour and the chain-grapple flow:
#   - Fire BTN_FIRE → head launches, sticks → ATTACHED at hit-time L
#   - Rope holds at L (no auto-contract). Pendulum swing.
#   - BTN_USE → release (state IDLE).
#   - BTN_FIRE while ATTACHED → release + fire new (state FLYING).
#   - BTN_FIRE while FLYING → silently swallowed (no double-head).
#
# The .log next to the PNGs captures every state transition via
# SHOT_LOG, plus per-second `grapple_swing dist=… rest=…` traces while
# attached so the swing distance can be eyeballed against the rest
# length. The contact sheet shows the firer mid-swing at several
# beats so the visual is recognisable as Tarzan (rope taut, body
# pendulum'd off the anchor) rather than the old "pinned to the wall"
# auto-contract behaviour.

window 1280 720
seed   6 6
out    build/shots/m5_grapple_swing
loadout - "Pulse Rifle" "Grappling Hook" Light Standard
contact_sheet sheet cols 4 cell 480 270

# Spawn mid-air, well above the high right platform and a bit to its
# left, so the mech is FALLING when the grapple fires — that way the
# rope visibly catches and swings the body around the anchor instead
# of the (slack-rope) "standing on a platform with a string attached"
# look you'd get from a grounded spawn.
spawn_at 2200 600

# Aim at the mid-map wall column (x=1760..1792). The hook flies down-
# left; the rope length comes out around 500 px.
aim 1780 1080

# ---- Beat 1: fire + attach + swing ---------------------------------
at  10 shot t010_idle
at  15 tap swap                  # active slot → Grappling Hook
at  20 shot t020_secondary
at  25 tap fire                  # spawn PROJ_GRAPPLE_HEAD
at  30 shot t030_head_inflight

# Head reaches the wall around tick ~47 with this aim — see the
# `grapple_attach anchor=… L=…` line in the log.
at  60 shot t060_attached

# Let gravity work the rope. With no auto-contract the mech swings
# below the anchor — pendulum motion. This is what the user wanted.
at 110 shot t110_mid_swing
at 160 shot t160_late_swing

# ---- Beat 2: BTN_USE disconnect ------------------------------------
at 180 tap use                   # BTN_USE edge → grapple_release
at 185 shot t185_after_release   # rope is gone, free fall begins

# ---- Beat 3: re-fire while previously released ---------------------
# Aim back at the wall column and fire again — IDLE → FLYING.
at 195 aim 1780 1080
at 200 tap fire                  # second grapple_fire
at 230 shot t230_second_attach

# ---- Beat 4: hold W to retract along the rope -----------------------
# Holding BTN_JET (W) while ATTACHED contracts the rope at 800 px/s
# (clamped at 60 px). Releasing W stops the contraction. The SHOT_LOG
# `grapple_swing dist=… rest=…` traces show rest dropping each second
# with " retracting" appended while W is held.
at 240 press jet                 # start zip-line up
at 250 shot t250_retract_start
at 280 release jet               # let go of W → rest stops shrinking
at 281 shot t281_retract_stopped

# ---- Beat 5: chain-grapple (fire WHILE ATTACHED) -------------------
# The whole point of the user request: be able to swing across the
# level by chaining grapples. A BTN_FIRE press while ATTACHED should
# auto-release the current rope and fire a new head.
#
# WeaponGrapplingHook.fire_rate_sec = 1.20 → 72-tick cooldown after
# every fire, so the chain re-fire has to wait at least 72 ticks past
# the most-recent grapple_fire (tick 200 → eligible at tick 272).
# Re-aim slightly off the old anchor so the new rope is visibly
# distinct.
at 290 aim 1850 1090
at 295 tap fire                  # chain re-fire (release + new fire)
at 300 shot t300_chain_inflight  # new head should be flying
at 330 shot t330_chain_attached  # newly-attached rope visible

# ---- Beat 6: final release -----------------------------------------
at 390 tap use
at 400 shot t400_final_released

at 450 end
